1. Choose a topic / application that suits your own interest.¶

Musical Metacreation

2. Select one scientific paper related to this topic.¶

Roberts, A., Engel, J., Mann, Y., Gillick, J., Kayacik, C., Nørly, S., ... & Eck, D. (2019). Magenta studio: Augmenting creativity with deep learning in ableton live. https://research.google/pubs/pub48280/

3. Study the paper.¶

https://storage.googleapis.com/pub-tools-public-publication-data/pdf/ab2b1a3cf41bd6c42b1d599382a40e05c22bea3b.pdf

4. Write a short summary.¶

Musical metacreation is the subject of creating software that is able to be musically creative. This paper covers some new advancements in this area. The team developed various models which will allow creative people to expand their musical horizon by allowing them to

  • extend existing (Continue) or generate new MIDI-sequences based on previous MIDI-sequences (Generate),
  • humanize sequences to make it sound more natural (Groove),
  • map a drum sequence to an arbitrary MIDI-sequence (Drumify),
  • morph multiple sequences into one (Interpolate).

All of these methods are designed to break creative barriers by assisting the artist. They do not aim to replace an artist. In order to make these methods available to the creative community, the team developed a set of "Virtual Studio Technology (VST)"-plugins for the Digital Audio Workstation (DAW) software Ableton Live, called "Magenta Studio". The plugins are easy to install and open-source, thus free to use.

The models utilize a variety of different techniques to achieve the previously described features. With this paper, the team also tried to get some insight into the creative community by surveying the early-adopters of the VST-plugins.

I personally like the idea of using tools like Magenta Studio, as it can help to overcome creative plateaus. As far as I understood from the paper, the models are fairly large and have been trained with large datasets. Within the conclusion sections, the authors briefly discuss the possiblity to develop personalized models by using techniques such as latent constraints (I assume this is some sort of transfer learning). I am curious to see how these personalized models can assist to generate new music in the future and whether the creativy community would actually start using the tools productively.

Up until now, the fields of musical metacreation has been unknown to me. However, I have been thinking about this topic in the past by myself (without me knowing of its existence). I find it intriguing, how easy to use these tools are and how effective they can be used to generate new music.
